text:
In case anyone cares, the difference between telekinesis and psychokinesis is that the former is a broader term that can encompass non-psychic phenomena. Both are from Greek.

Psychokinesis means "moving stuff with your mind/soul", whereas telekinesis means "moving stuff from a distance". Therefore, despite telekinesis often being mentioned in fiction as a psychic ability (synonymous with psychokinesis), the term also encompesses phenomena like manipulating 'mass effect', or using the Force, or dark matter, or dark energy, or some kind of extra dimension in order to move objects from a distance. Psychokinesis is therefore a subset of telekinesis.

Telekinesis used to be a much more common term than psychokinesis, thanks to the X-Men comics/cartoons always being very careful to distinguish between telekinesis and telepathy, using the terms very often when dscribing the powers of Professor, X, Jean Grey, Psylocke, Emma Frost, etc. Psychokinesis only really emerged as a 'thing' in fiction thanks to Metal Gear Solid's Psycho Mantis character.

text:
¬†@mad0813¬† Strictly speaking she's not necessarily the most popular. I for one an subbed to over 50 channels on this platform that I haven't even watched a single video on in over five years, if not much longer.

That's mostly just nitpicking about specifics though, the overall point you had is still absolutely true. Any of the Hololive girls would be great promotion for any game publisher or even the consoles themselves. It's such an obvious business opportunity that even stubborn assed Japanese companies run by stubborn assed old men stuck on tradition and such for everything take notice and utilize it very often.
author: @Glomoro

text:
¬†@Glomoro¬† No, Gura is the most popular Vtuber, nobody else has more views per minute than she does. Pekora, Marine, and Aqua can pull some insane numbers too but not as much as Gura.

She doesn't have the most simps though; even in the West, Kiara and Calli have more Super Chat than her even though Gura has WAY more views. Coco, Rushia, Kanata, and Flare pull RIDICULOUS simp numbers too, especially considering their views, but JP fans do tend to simp harder than Western ones.
author: @bobjones4469

text:
¬†@bobjones4469¬† You sort of just added to my own point. You can't decide their popularity numerically by one factor alone. It'd have to be a combination of things, and some of that information might also only be in the analytics for the channel that we don't have access to.

Not to mention despite the term's inherent tie to Youtube, there are VTubers on other platforms. How should we compare the Youtube and Twitch numbers, for instance? Hell, what about Projekt Melody, who is on Youtube, Twitch, Chaturbate, PornHub, Only Fans... I mean, am I forgetting any? She's everywhere except maybe more musically inclined places like Spotify... but Calli is one, so how do we compare that? 

How much is just the same people following and generating views or whatever else on all of the platforms any individual VTuber is on, and how much is actually different people only following and all that on a particular platform? How do we count things for the "OG," Kizuna AI? As far as I'm aware that has been at least two different people behind the avatar on the main account alone, so would we count this one in a total sense or based on particular chunks of time where we suspect the person has changed out.

With the amount of different numbers involved that could be tied to something like "popularity," none them stands out as a perfect thing to use on its own.
author: @Glomoro

text:
¬†@bobjones4469¬† Well at least according to Socialblade, Gura got 17.391 million views last 30 days while Pekora got 19.343 million. (This actually surprised me, then again I do love Peko too :]) So I suppose Glomoro has a point.

Though Pekora's had dipped from last month by 0.2% and Gura's views were up by a whopping 25%, so Gura is certainly the fastest growing by many factors right now, that's for sure.
author: @sarcasm-83

text:
¬†@Glomoro¬† Well you are very right in that subscribers don't really mean anything, if the views aren't there. As well as on Projekt Melody probably practically drowning in money right now.

But I still would agree with Bob that Gura is absolutely blowing up. Though, entire Hololive is gaining mad traction. Holo-EN really lit a fire under the whole company - at least so it seems to me.
Which is very cool. Also glad that no one in Hololive is treating it as a popularity contest!
author: @sarcasm-83

text: ¬†@sarcasm-83¬† I mean, I never said she wasn't blowing up, in fact in the original comment I edited down so that it didn't need a "read more" I actually remember having typed something along the lines of "She is perhaps the fastest growing VTuber, but" as the lead in to the points about how we should even measure popularity.
author: @Glomoro

text: ¬†@Glomoro¬† Yeah I do agree you have a good point there. Many different types of "popularity" these days!
